==Old Englsh==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon ''winnan'' (Dutch [[winnen]]), Old High German ''winnan'', Old Norse [[vinna]] (Swedish [[vinna]]), Gothic [[𐍅𐌹𐌽𐌽𐌰𐌽]].
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'wɪn:an/}}

===Verb===
'''winnan''' (class III strong: ''3 singular present'' '''[[winneþ]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[wann]]''' or '''[[wonn]]''', ''3 plural preterite'' '''[[wunnon]]''', ''past participle'' '''[[wunnen]]''')
# [[struggle]], [[suffer]], [[contend]]
#:''A ic wite wonn minra wræcsiþa.''  I always suffered the torment of my exile-journeys.  (‘The Wife's Lament’)

